The expert’s strategy is to move the agent toward the star by following a path of "drawn" tiles, using the left and right arrow tiles to shift the agent horizontally when needed. Initially, the expert repeatedly clicks on empty cells in a column above the drawn path, but the agent does not move until the left or right arrow tile is clicked. Once the agent is adjacent to a left or right arrow tile (located at the bottom of the drawn path), the expert clicks the arrow tile, causing the agent to move horizontally along the row of drawn tiles. The expert continues to click the appropriate arrow tile at each step, shifting the agent left or right as needed, and then repeats this process, moving the agent up the drawn path toward the star, using the arrows to change columns when necessary. The expert never clicks on the star directly or on the agent itself, and only uses the arrow tiles to move the agent horizontally, while vertical movement is achieved by the agent being "carried" up the drawn path as the arrows are used.

The game dynamics observed are as follows: The environment is a grid with special tiles: "drawn" tiles form a path, "star" is the goal, and "left_arrow"/"right_arrow" tiles at the end of the drawn path enable horizontal movement. The agent starts at the bottom of the drawn path and cannot move by clicking empty cells; only clicking on the arrow tiles causes the agent to move horizontally by one cell per click, provided the agent is aligned with the arrow row. After each horizontal move, the agent remains on the drawn path, and the process can be repeated to move the agent left or right along the path. The agent cannot move vertically by direct action; instead, the drawn path is constructed such that horizontal movement via arrows also results in the agent being positioned higher up the path, eventually reaching the star. The environment is deterministic, and only arrow tiles affect the agent’s position, while other clicks have no effect.